title: The Lambach Article – *“Monarchismus”*
tags: event
view-if: (year >= 1928 and month >= 7 and dnvp_votes < 14 and lambach_seen = 0) or (year >= 1929 and lambach_seen = 0 and (dnvp_win = 2 or dnvp_win = 0))
priority: 1
on-arrival: lambach_seen = 1; 

= Lambach Article - "Monarchy"

Following catastrophic polling results—which saw the DNVP plummet from 20% to [+ dnvp_r +]%—Kuno von Westarp has resigned. While he remains the acting leader until a successor is chosen, his departure has left a significant power vacuum.
​The internal crisis intensified following Walther Lambach’s publication of "Monarchy." In the article, Lambach argues that authoritarian nostalgia and "all-or-nothing" monarchist policies are futile. Instead, he advocates for a pragmatic shift: cooperating with republican parties to build a united front against the SPD and KPD.

​This has ignited a civil war within the party:
​The Hugenberg Fraction: Alfred Hugenberg is leading a coalition of radicals, officers, and aristocrats to purge Lambach from the party and maintain a hardline anti-republican stance.
​The Moderate/Reformed Opposition: A diverse group of civilians, non-Hugenbergite royalists, and landowners are rallying behind either the traditional leadership of Westarp or the reformist vision of Hartwig, Lambach and Treviranus.
​
​We face a pivotal choice in how to handle the DNVP’s fragmentation:

​The Reformist Path (Hartwig/Lambach/Treviranus): Supporting this wing is unlikely to win us a direct ally—the DNVP remains ideologically hostile to our social reforms and the SPD. However, it could successfully integrate them into the republican framework, stabilizing the state.
​The Accelerationist Path (Hugenberg): Conversely, we could covertly support the Hugenbergites. This would further alienate the DNVP from the republican system, potentially radicalizing them to the point where the broader bourgeoisie feels forced to cooperate with us out of necessity.

